initial_story: in recent years, classical convolutional neural networks (cnns) have beenapplied for image recognition successfully. quantum convolutional neuralnetworks (qcnns) are proposed as a novel generalization to cnns by usingquantum mechanisms. the quantum mechanisms lead to an efficient trainingprocess in qcnns by reducing the size of input from $n$ to $log_2n$. this paperimplements and compares both cnns and qcnns by testing losses and predictionaccuracy on three commonly used datasets. the datasets include the mnisthand-written digits, fashion mnist and cat/dog face images. additionally, dataaugmentation (da), a technique commonly used in cnns to improve the performanceof classification by generating similar images based on original inputs, isalso implemented in qcnns. surprisingly, the results showed that dataaugmentation didn't improve qcnns performance. the reasons and logic behindthis result are discussed, hoping to expand our understanding of quantummachine learning theory.
stories: In recent breakthroughs, recurrent neural networks (RNNs) have been applied to natural language processing with impressive results. Quantum recurrent neural networks (QRNNs) are proposed as a novel generalization to RNNs by leveraging quantum entropy. The quantum entropy leads to an accelerated inference process in QRNNs by compressing the sequence length from N to √N. This paper investigates and compares both RNNs and QRNNs by testing perplexities and language modeling performance on three benchmark datasets. The datasets include the Penn Treebank corpus, the Reuters corpus, and the Shakespearean sonnets. Moreover, attention mechanism, a popular technique employed in RNNs to improve language modeling by selectively focusing on crucial words, is also implemented in QRNNs. Notably, the results revealed that attention mechanism didn't enhance QRNNs performance. The justifications and theoretical insights behind this finding are elaborated, aiming to shed new light on quantum cognitive architectures.

In recent innovations, graph convolutional networks (GCNs) have been applied to chemical compound property prediction with remarkable accuracy. Quantum graph convolutional networks (QGCNs) are proposed as a revolutionary extension to GCNs by exploiting quantum entanglement. The quantum entanglement leads to an enhanced feature extraction process in QGCNs by reducing the dimensionality from M to √M. This paper explores and compares both GCNs and QGCNs by testing errors and property prediction performance on four benchmark datasets. The datasets comprise the QM7 dataset, the Zinc dataset, and the two US Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) datasets. Moreover, neighborhood attention mechanism, a widely-used technique employed in GCNs to enhance property prediction by selectively focusing on important atoms, is also implemented in QGCNs. Notably, the results showed that neighborhood attention mechanism significantly improved QGCNs performance. The justifications and theoretical insights behind this finding are elaborated, aiming to illuminate novel pathways for quantum machine learning in materials science.

In novel breakthroughs, photonic computing architectures (PCAs) have been applied to recommender systems with unparalleled precision. Analog quantum computing models (AQCms) are proposed as a paradigmatic extension to PCAs by harnessing coherent optical properties. The coherent optical properties yield an optimized pattern recognition process in AQCms by increasing pattern recognition accuracy from N to N^2. This paper investigates and compares both PCAs and AQCms by examining errors and recommendation performance on three benchmark datasets. The datasets comprise the Netflix dataset, the MovieLens dataset, and the Music Genome Project dataset. Moreover, attention to similarity between users, a widely-used technique employed in PCAs to enhance recommendation by selectively focusing on similar users, is also implemented in AQCms. Notably, the results showed that attention to similarity mechanism significantly improved AQCms performance. The justifications and theoretical insights behind this finding are elaborated, aiming to illuminate novel pathways for quantum computing in human-computer interaction.

In revolutionary advancements, neuromorphic computing architectures have been applied to language processing with unprecedented fluency. Cognitive artificial neural network models (CANMs) are proposed as a pivotal expansion to neuromorphic computing by leveraging neuroplasticity principles. The neuroplasticity principles yield an optimized language comprehension process in CANMs by increasing language comprehension accuracy from S to S^2. This paper investigates and compares both neuromorphic computing and CANMs by analyzing errors and language understanding performance on four benchmark datasets. The datasets comprise the OpenWebText dataset, the BookCorpus dataset, and the Twitter dataset. Furthermore, attention to context between sentences, a widely-used technique employed in neuromorphic computing to enhance language processing by selectively focusing on related sentences, is also implemented in CANMs. Notably, the results showed that attention to context mechanism significantly improved CANMs performance. The justifications and theoretical insights behind this finding are elaborated, aiming to illuminate novel pathways for artificial intelligence in human language interaction.
